  <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim" aria-labelledby="faq-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <h2 id="faq-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-10">
        Frequently Asked <span class="text-accent">Questions</span>
      </h2>

      <div class="space-y-4">
        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8" open>
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            What is a flighted conveyor?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>A flighted conveyor is a belt conveyor with raised cleats, flights, or partitions bonded to the belt surface at regular intervals. The flights prevent product from sliding backward on inclines, allowing the conveyor to move bulk, granular, and small items at angles from 30 to 90 degrees.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            What is the difference between flighted and scoop conveyors?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>Flighted conveyors use flat or angled cleats to prevent rollback on inclines up to 45-60 degrees. Scoop conveyors use enclosed bucket-shaped containers that fully retain product at angles up to 90 degrees (vertical). Scoops protect fragile products better but cost more and have lower throughput than cleated belts.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            What incline angle can a flighted conveyor handle?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>Standard cleats handle 30-45 degrees. Sidewall cleated belts handle 45-90 degrees. Scoop and bucket conveyors handle 60-90 degrees. The maximum angle depends on product characteristics , free-flowing products need taller flights and lower angles, while cohesive products tolerate steeper angles with shorter flights.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            Are flighted conveyors available in food-grade designs?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>Yes. Food-grade versions use FDA-compliant polyurethane or silicone belts with integrally molded flights, stainless steel frames, IP69K motors, and tool-free belt removal for cleaning. Dorner, Nercon, and UniTrak offer <a href="/industries/food-conveyors/sanitary/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">sanitary flighted conveyors</a> meeting USDA requirements.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
      </div>
    </div>
